text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Diminutives%0a%0a:Author: meturner%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA discussion of the formation of the diminutive in various languages. %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aDiminutives are words that have been modified to convey a meaning either related to reduced size or emotional closeness of relationship. Examples of this phenomenon are found in languages across the world, with some using it extensively. %0a%0aIn English, the diminutive is often seen in words with the suffixes [-et(te)] and [-ie]. Examples include “kitchenette” (small kitchen), “ringlet” (small curl of hair), “doggie” (cute dog), and “hubbie” (term of endearment for a husband). %0a%0aThough the diminutive is commonly used in English, there are many languages that use it in even broader contexts: Russian, for example, has a huge number of diminutive suffixes and other modifiers that can be added to names to indicate closeness. In the ThoughtCo article, for example, the given name Maria can be changed to Masha, Mashenka, Mashunechka, Mashunya, Marusya, or Mashka depending on the situation, the speaker, and the addressee. These modifications can apply to nouns as well, modifying them to be used as pet names between friends, family, or partners: [рыбы]/[ryby] (fish) becomes [рыбочка]/[rybochka], or little fish, when used as a term of endearment. %0a%0aExamples of the diminutive can also be found in Dutch, Polish, Spanish, and Latin, among many others. %0a%0a%0ahttps://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/diminutive%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diminutive%0ahttps://www.thoughtco.com/russian-nicknames-and-diminutives-1502309%0ahttps://omniglot.com/language/endearment/russian.htm%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221210-041350-777250#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Isolating language diminutives %0a-> - nathandeyak%0a-> [-09.12.2022 - 20:13-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221210-041350-777250 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aIt is interesting to look at diminutives in isolating languages such as Mandarin Chinese. In many languages, especially Indo-European languages, we usually see diminutives take a morphological form, but in Chinese morphology is extremely limited. Instead, reduplication of the whole word is used, possibly in order to imitate babbling speech from infants to provide a diminutive connotation. More examples are given in the following article:%0a%0ahttps://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=23204%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221210-041350-777250#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: F:)%0a(:Category: Varia:)%0a(:Title: Diminutives:)
